# Project-specific redaction patterns for the /second-opinion skill.
#
# This file is OPTIONAL. The skill already redacts universal credential
# shapes (cloud keys, DB DSNs, PEM, JWT, vendor-agnostic *_SECRET=... env
# vars, Telegram bot tokens, bearer tokens). Add patterns here only for
# strings that no general regex can safely catch in your project:
#
#   - internal hostnames
#   - internal service IDs
#   - schema / table names you do not want sent to OpenAI
#   - custom token formats
#   - any project-private string class
#
# How to use:
#   cp .claude/redact-patterns.txt.example .claude/redact-patterns.txt
#   $EDITOR .claude/redact-patterns.txt
#
# Format:
#   - One regex per line.
#   - Anything matching the regex is replaced with [REDACTED].
#   - Lines starting with # are comments and are ignored.
#   - Empty lines are ignored.
#   - Regex syntax is awk POSIX extended. Test patterns with:
#       echo 'sample text' | awk '{ gsub(/your-regex/, "[REDACTED]"); print }'
#
# Safety notes:
#   - Prefer narrow patterns over broad ones to keep findings useful.
#     A pattern matching `[a-z]+` would redact everything.
#   - Patterns are applied per-line, so multi-line secrets need multi-line
#     handling (the skill does that for PEM blocks already).
#
# Examples (uncomment and adapt to your project):

# Internal hostnames:
# \b[a-z0-9.-]+\.internal\.example\.com\b
# \bgt\.devopspoint\.io\b

# Internal service IDs:
# \bsvc-[a-z0-9]{8,}\b

# Custom token formats (replace MYCO with your prefix):
# \bMYCO_[A-Z0-9]{16,}\b

# Schema / table names you do not want sent:
# \b(orders_private|customer_pii|fraud_signals)\b
